context: In the 16th century, <a0_0><b5_0>Count Hieronymus Schlick of Bohemia<b5_0/><a0_0/> began minting coins known as Joachimstalers (from German thal, or nowadays usually Tal, "valley", cognate with "dale" in English), named for Joachimstal, the valley where the <a2_0><b7_0>silver<b7_0/><a2_0/> was mined (St. Joachim's Valley, now <a1_0><b6_0>Jáchymov<b6_0/><a1_0/>; then part of the Kingdom of Bohemia, now part of the Czech Republic). Joachimstaler was later shortened to the German Taler, a word that eventually found its way into Danish and Swedish as daler, Norwegian as dalar and daler, Dutch as daler or daalder, Ethiopian as ታላሪ (talari), Hungarian as tallér, Italian as <a3_0><b8_0>tallero<b8_0/><a3_0/>, and English as dollar. Alternatively, thaler is said to come from the German coin <a4_0><b9_0>Guldengroschen<b9_0/><a4_0/> ("great guilder", being of silver but equal in value to a gold guilder), minted from the silver from Joachimsthal.
